<?php $__env->startSection('content'); ?><p>The 8.02am train from Oxford to London Marylebone was the most overcrowded in England and Wales last autumn, as new figures reveal the top ten most pack trains.</p>

<p>There were nearly twice as many standard class passengers as the registered capacity when the two-carriage Chiltern Railways service arrived in London on a weekday, giving it a load factor of 196 per cent. </p>

<p>The Department for Transport (DfT), which published the data, said constraints on the number of available carriages limited the operator's ability to cope with rising demand.</p>

<p>The 8.02am train from Oxford to London Marylebone was the most overcrowded in England and Wales last autumn, as new figures reveal the top ten most pack trains </p>

<p>Commuters board a London Overground train today. The 7.38am Enfield Town to London Liverpool Street train was the third most packed in England and Wales this time last year</p>

<p>The 7.32am South Western Railway train from Woking to London Waterloo was the second most overcrowded train, with a load factor of 182 per cent when it reached its destination.</p>

<p>Load factor refers to the number of passengers as a percentage of the maximum capacity at the busiest point in a journey.</p>

<p>Other services in the top 10 most packed trains include the 3.08pm Great Western Railway train from Weymouth to Gloucester, which has a load factor of 178 per cent.</p>

